MEDIUM|internal/payload/grounding.go:44|The changedLines and RangeBuilder.BuildChangedLines docstrings state grounding "adds no git subprocess" once a payload build ran, and the AC3 test TestRangeBuilder_GroundingReusesPayloadGitProcesses only exercises ModeFiles. But only files-mode populates the zeroCtx cache (via rangeChunks). The default roster mode is blocks (registry/project.go:16), which builds via fcChunks/plainChunks and never calls zeroCtxChunks. So under the default/most-common config, computeGroundingData still spawns one --unified=0 subprocess in grounding — the reuse elides validateRange + --name-status but NOT the zero-context diff. The zero-subprocess claim is only true for files-mode rosters.|Qualify both docstrings in grounding.go:44-50 and rangebuilder.go:63-67 to say reuse always elides validateRange + --name-status, and additionally elides --unified=0 ONLY when a zeroCtx-consuming mode (files) already ran. Add a sibling test that builds ModeBlocks then BuildChangedLines and asserts execCount increases by exactly 1, documenting the residual grounding process for non-files rosters.|maintainability|30|internal/payload/grounding.go:44-50; internal/payload/rangebuilder_test.go:28-39; internal/payload/diff.go:479-515|claude
LOW|internal/payload/rangebuilder.go:54|RangeBuilder.BuildEntries re-inlines the exact payload-mode validation and error string ("unknown payload mode '%s': must be one of diff, blocks, files") that already exists at three other sites (builder.go Build, package-level BuildEntries, and fileBody default). Four copies of the same mode set + message. If a payload mode is ever added or the message reworded, one copy will drift and the RangeBuilder path will silently disagree with the package-level contract it claims to mirror.|Extract a package-private validatePayloadMode(mode) error (or a shared knownMode set) and call it from all four sites. Verify TestRangeBuilder_UnknownModeError and the package-level equivalents still pass.|maintainability|15|internal/payload/rangebuilder.go:53-56|claude
LOW|internal/fanout/review.go:411|computeGroundingData now gates on req.Range emptiness but, when rb != nil, computes changed lines from rb's OWN stored base/head (rb.BuildChangedLines uses b.base/b.head), ignoring req.Range entirely. Every current caller builds rb from the same req.Range in the same function so they always agree, but the invariant is now implicit; a future edit that grounds a req whose range differs from the rb it was handed would silently anchor grounding to the wrong range with no error (fail-open would not trigger).|Either assert rb's range matches req.Range inside computeGroundingData (cheap in-memory check), or add a doc line on RangeBuilder stating the caller must construct it from the same req.Range it later grounds. Verify all buildPayloads/computeGroundingData call sites (review.go:239/397, resume.go:283/315) still pass a matched pair.|maintainability|15|internal/fanout/review.go:411-431|claude
LOW|internal/fanout/review.go:394|The grounding-semantics-unchanged guarantee is tested only at the payload layer (TestRangeBuilder_ChangedLinesMatchesStandalone). The fan-out threading — buildPayloads returning rb, finalizePreparedReview/PrepareResume passing it into computeGroundingData, and the nil-rb fallback in PrepareReviewFromDiff — has no test asserting PreparedReview.Changed equals the pre-epic standalone payload.BuildChangedLines output. A regression that threads a wrong/nil rb on the git-range path would compile and the payload tests would stay green.|Add a fanout test that runs PrepareReview on a temp repo with a known diff and asserts p.Changed matches payload.BuildChangedLines(ctx, repo, base, head), plus one asserting the diff-ingestion path yields GroundingDisabledReason "range-less". Verify with go test ./internal/fanout/.|testing|30|internal/fanout/review.go:394-397; internal/fanout/resume.go:315|claude

